values.comments:
This course is a general overview of astronomical theories, designed for non-majors. The course progresses from the solar system and extraterrestrial life to the life cycles of stars and the structures of galaxies and the universe. It fulfills the Physical World Sector requirement, and has no prerequisites. There are generally two midterms, a final, and homework assignments. The textbook used is The Cosmic Perspective 4e.

Students tended to describe the course as interesting and entertaining, saying that they “learned a lot.” Most saw it as an easy way for “people afraid of science at Penn” to fulfill the Physical World requirement, though a few students noted that the math used could be difficult at times. &#8232;&#8232;

Students heaped praise on Professor Sako, commending his passion for the subject matter as well as his effective communication of the material. Professor Sako was described as very helpful, and made time for office hours and review. One student noted that he “never showed anger or frustration at my lack of understanding.” &#8232;&#8232;

Although students thought that the work for this course was not time-consuming, a few assignments were described as “pointless.” Students disagreed about grading, some saying that tests were graded generously, and others that later ones were graded harshly “because the averages started out too high” on early tests. Overall, students agreed that there was a lot of material, but that it was covered at a “good pace.”
